      <!-- Executive Summary -->
      <h2>Executive Summary</h2>
      <p>Every NHS organisation already possesses the raw material of AI ethics: co-produced vision and values, developed with patients, carers, and staff. These documents are not aspirational posters. They encode what an organisation believes about dignity, safety, equity, and accountability.</p>
      <p>This paper argues that sustainable AI governance in the NHS should begin there — and build upward. By mapping the established pillars of AI ethics onto existing organisational values, and then designing a runtime monitoring layer that accounts for real human behaviour rather than idealised compliance, NHS organisations can move from governance as language to governance as verifiable operation.</p>
      <p>This is not a proposal to build new technology from scratch. It is a framework for using what exists more intelligently — and for being honest about where the gaps are.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-title">Central Proposition</div>
        <p>The question for NHS AI governance is not <em>'Do we have a policy?'</em> It is: <em>'Can we show, at the point of clinical action, that only admissible conduct occurred — and that human oversight was genuinely exercised, not merely performed?'</em></p>
      </div>

      <!-- The Problem -->
      <h2>The Problem: Governance Language Without Governed Operation</h2>
      <p>Most NHS AI governance frameworks are not inadequate. They are incomplete. They describe, document, audit, and reconstruct. What they rarely do is govern in real time — at the moment a clinical decision is made, a note is generated, or a triage recommendation is accepted.</p>
      <p>This gap matters because the highest-risk moments in AI-assisted care are not detectable after the fact. They occur in the interaction between a clinician and an AI system: the acceptance without review, the override that does not happen, the recommendation followed without documented clinical reasoning.</p>
      <p>Current frameworks typically provide:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Policies and standards (DCB0129, DCB0160, DSPT, NHSE AI framework)</li>
        <li>Pre-deployment assessment and clinical safety cases</li>
        <li>Post-hoc audit trails and dashboards</li>
        <li>Vendor assurance documentation</li>
        <li>Governance committee structures</li>
      </ul>
      <p>What they rarely provide is a live, computable layer that can demonstrate — at the execution boundary — that human oversight was genuinely present, that the system behaved within its approved parameters, and that specific patient populations were not disadvantaged by automation patterns.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <div class="callout-title">⚠ The Rubber-Stamping Problem</div>
        <p>A clinician who accepts an AI-generated clinical note in three seconds has technically completed the 'human in the loop' step. But they have not exercised clinical judgment. Governance frameworks that cannot distinguish between performed compliance and real oversight are producing a false sense of assurance — and a genuine safety exposure.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- The Foundation -->
      <h2>The Existing Foundation: Trust Values as Ethical Substrate</h2>
      <p>Every NHS organisation has a set of co-produced values. These are not peripheral documents. They represent the outcome of genuine engagement with patients, carers, clinical staff, and communities. They articulate what the organisation believes about how care should be delivered and how people should be treated.</p>
      <p>For the purposes of AI governance, these values are the ethical ground truth. They are the answer to the question: 'What does good look like in this organisation?' — a question that AI ethics frameworks cannot answer generically.</p>
      <p>The translation does not require new values. It requires organisations to take their existing values seriously as operational commitments — including in digital environments.</p>

      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Organisational Value</th><th>AI Governance Implication</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>We listen</td><td>AI outputs must not override patient-expressed preferences. Human review must include a record of patient voice where it exists in the record.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>We are compassionate</td><td>AI-assisted triage must not systematically deprioritise patients with complex presentations or protected characteristics.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>We take responsibility</td><td>Every AI-generated clinical action must have a named, accountable clinician. Anonymised AI outputs are not permissible in clinical records.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>We keep you safe</td><td>Any AI system whose performance has drifted from its approved safety case must trigger immediate clinical review, not a quarterly report.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>We work together</td><td>AI governance is not a digital team responsibility. Clinical leaders, patient representatives, and operational managers share accountability.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <!-- AI Ethics Pillars -->
      <h2>Integrating the Pillars of AI Ethics</h2>
      <p>International AI ethics frameworks — including those from the WHO, OECD, and the NHS AI Lab — converge on a consistent set of principles. These are not alternatives to Trust values. They are the technical vocabulary that allows values to be operationalised in AI systems.</p>

      <table class="ethics-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Pillar</th><th>Core Commitment</th><th>NHS Governance Question</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Beneficence</td><td>AI should benefit patients and populations</td><td>Can we demonstrate net clinical benefit, including for underserved groups?</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Non-maleficence</td><td>AI should not cause harm — including through inaction or delay</td><td>Are we monitoring for harm caused by over-reliance, automation bias, or delayed human review?</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Autonomy</td><td>Patients and clinicians retain meaningful choice</td><td>Is consent to AI involvement documented? Can clinicians meaningfully override AI recommendations?</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Justice &amp; Equity</td><td>AI should not exacerbate health inequalities</td><td>Are we monitoring AI performance disaggregated by ethnicity, deprivation, age, and gender?</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Explicability</td><td>AI decisions should be understandable to those affected</td><td>Can a patient ask how an AI contributed to their care, and receive a meaningful answer?</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Accountability</td><td>Responsibility for AI conduct must be clearly assigned</td><td>Is there a named clinician accountable for every AI-assisted clinical action?</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <!-- Real Human Behaviour -->
      <h2>Designing for Real Human Behaviour</h2>
      <p>This is the most neglected dimension of AI governance — and the most important. Every governance framework implicitly assumes a rational, attentive, unhurried clinician who reads every AI output carefully, exercises independent judgment, documents their reasoning, and flags anomalies. This clinician does not exist at scale.</p>

      <h3>Automation Bias</h3>
      <p>Clinicians systematically favour AI recommendations over their own judgment, particularly under time pressure. The effect is stronger when AI outputs are presented with confidence scores, when the clinician is fatigued, and when the AI has a track record of accuracy. Governance that does not monitor for automation bias is not monitoring the right thing.</p>

      <h3>Rubber-Stamping</h3>
      <p>When human review becomes a step in a workflow rather than an act of clinical judgment, it loses its protective function. Time-on-task data, amendment rates, and override patterns are behavioural proxies for genuine oversight. These should be monitored — not as disciplinary tools, but as system-level safety signals.</p>

      <h3>Alert Fatigue</h3>
      <p>A governance layer that generates too many alerts will be ignored. Clinical teams in high-pressure environments have finite attention. Any alert mechanism must be designed with the same discipline as clinical decision support: precise, actionable, and calibrated to interrupt only when it genuinely matters.</p>

      <h3>Gaming Under Pressure</h3>
      <p>Clinicians working under capacity pressure will find the path of least resistance through any compliance layer. If clicking 'reviewed' takes three seconds and has no consequence, it will take three seconds. Governance design must anticipate this — not by punishing individuals, but by making the compliant path the easiest path.</p>

      <h3>Equity Blind Spots</h3>
      <p>Automation bias compounds existing inequality. If an AI system performs better for white male patients in the training data, and clinicians disproportionately defer to its recommendations for minority ethnic patients — who may have less documentation in the record — the result is a governance-invisible harm. Equity monitoring must be built in from the start, not retrospectively.</p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        "Design for the clinician on a busy Friday afternoon — not the clinician in the pilot study. If the framework only works under ideal conditions, it does not work."
      </div>

      <!-- The Framework -->
      <h2>A Proposed Framework: The Values-Anchored Governance Layer</h2>
      <p>The framework has four operational layers, built on a foundation that already exists in every NHS organisation.</p>

      <div class="framework">
        <div class="layer l4">
          <div class="layer-tag">Layer 4</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <div class="layer-name">Assurance Surface</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">Verifiable reporting for DCB0129/0160, CQC, and NHS England AI regulation. Generates structured evidence capable of demonstrating trustworthy operation — not just compliance.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="layer l3">
          <div class="layer-tag">Layer 3</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <div class="layer-name">Alert Engine</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">Proactive escalation when human guardrails fail, drift is detected, or equity signals emerge. Calibrated to interrupt only when it genuinely matters.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="layer l2">
          <div class="layer-tag">Layer 2</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <div class="layer-name">Runtime Monitor</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">Watches human behaviour in relation to AI: HITL integrity, automation bias signals, rubber-stamping patterns, model drift, and population equity. Passive, not obstructive.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="layer l1">
          <div class="layer-tag">Layer 1</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <div class="layer-name">Policy Substrate</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">Organisational values and AI ethics pillars encoded as live, computable rules — not PDFs on an intranet. Precise enough to be testable.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="layer l0">
          <div class="layer-tag">Foundation</div>
          <div class="layer-body">
            <div class="layer-name">Co-Produced Trust Values</div>
            <div class="layer-desc">Developed with patients, carers, and staff. The ethical ground truth already present in every NHS organisation. Not imported. Not generic. Yours.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Challenges -->
      <h2>Challenges and Honest Caveats</h2>
      <div class="callout" style="background:#F5F5F5;border-color:var(--muted);">
        <div class="callout-title" style="color:var(--muted);">A note on intellectual honesty</div>
        <p>A framework that does not acknowledge its own constraints is not a framework — it is a pitch.</p>
      </div>

      <ol class="numbered-list">
        <li>
          <span class="num">01</span>
          <div><strong>Vendor API access is the critical dependency.</strong> EHR vendors do not routinely expose the interaction-level data required to monitor HITL integrity. This must become a standard procurement condition for all AI system deployments. Without it, runtime monitoring is not possible.</div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="num">02</span>
          <div><strong>Latency risk in emergency contexts.</strong> Any pre-execution governance step that introduces delay is itself a patient safety risk. The framework described here operates primarily through passive monitoring and post-hoc alerting, not execution blocking. The distinction matters and must be preserved in implementation.</div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="num">03</span>
          <div><strong>Encoding ethics is technically hard and politically contested.</strong> What counts as 'genuine' human oversight? Organisations will disagree. Computable rules require precision, and precision exposes choices that vague policies conceal. This is a feature, not a bug — but it requires clinical and IG leadership, not just technical teams.</div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="num">04</span>
          <div><strong>This space is not empty.</strong> NHS England's AI and Digital Regulations Service, the MHRA's SaMD framework, and the NHS AI Lab's model monitoring workstreams are all developing in this territory. Any implementation must build from, and contribute to, these national efforts — not replicate them in silos.</div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="num">05</span>
          <div><strong>Workforce readiness is a governance precondition.</strong> A monitoring layer deployed into a team that has not been engaged, educated, and involved in its design will be experienced as surveillance. Clinical engagement is not a communications step. It is a safety requirement.</div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <!-- Call to Action -->
      <h2>A Call for System-Level Action</h2>
      <p>The NHS does not lack commitment to ethical AI. It lacks a coherent method for translating that commitment into demonstrable, real-time conduct. This framework proposes a practical path forward — not through new values, but through the more demanding work of taking existing values seriously.</p>
      <p>Three things would move this forward at system level:</p>

      <div class="callout" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
        <div class="callout-title">Ask 01 — Mandate vendor API transparency</div>
        <p>Governance cannot monitor what it cannot see. Make interaction-level data a standard condition of all NHS AI deployment contracts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="callout" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
        <div class="callout-title">Ask 02 — Commission a national equity monitoring standard</div>
        <p>Individual trusts should not have to design this alone. AI performance must be monitored disaggregated by ethnicity, age, deprivation index, and gender — as a national minimum.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="callout" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
        <div class="callout-title">Ask 03 — Build a shared computable policy library</div>
        <p>A repository of live governance rules mapped to DCB0129/0160 requirements, adapted from clinical safety community expertise. The clinical safety community should lead this — they have the depth.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        "Governance that cannot distinguish between performed compliance and genuine human oversight is not governance. It is documentation. NHS patients deserve the difference."
      </div>

    </div><!-- /paper-body -->
  </div>
</section>

